===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|fr|apologie}}, from {{der|en|LL.|apologia}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἀπολογία||a speech in defence}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπολογοῦμαι||I speak in my defense}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπόλογος||an account, story}}, from {{m|grc|ἀπό||from, off}} (see ''[[apo-]]'') + {{m|grc|λόγος||speech}}. {{doublet|en|apologia}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/əˈpɒl.ə.dʒi/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-apology.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɒlədʒi|s=4}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An expression of [[remorse]] or [[regret]] for having said or done something that [[harm]]ed another: an instance of [[apologize|apologizing]] (saying that one is [[sorry]]).
#: {{ux|en|What he said really hurt my feelings, but his '''apology''' sounded so sincere that I couldn't help but forgive him.}}
#: {{ux|en|The CEO made a public '''apology''' for the scandal, and promised full cooperation with the authorities.}}
# A formal [[justification]], [[defence]].
#: {{ux|en|The '''Apology''' of Socrates.}}
#: {{syn|en|apologia}}
# Anything provided as a [[substitute]]; a [[makeshift]].
#: {{ux|en|a poor '''apology''' for a hotel room}}
#* {{RQ:Dickens Bleak House|20}}
#*: [He] goes to work devising '''apologies''' for window curtains.

